a blackbox in the car ?
U.S. road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the sinking highway system , and believe the solution has been found in a small black box that finds space in the dashboard of each car .
the devices , which record every mile and report the information to the authorities , are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state &apos;s planning offices to revise the outdated system to fund U.S. roads .
the normally more boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked intense debate with colorful alliances .
libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups , arguing that the government can use the small boxes to record the miles - and possibly even where they were driven - and then use the information to calculate tax rulings .
the Tea Party is horrified .
the American Civil Liberties Union ( ACLU ) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns .
but while Congress cannot agree on an approach , several states are no longer waiting .
they are currently examining how they can switch to a system over the next decade where drivers pay per driven mile .
thousands of motorists have already tested the tachograph , some of which are equipped with GPS surveillance .
this is really a must for our country .
&quot; it &apos;s nothing we &apos;ll only possibly use , &quot; said Hasan Ikhrata , managing director of the Southern California Assn. of Governments , which plans a record of driving miles among all California motorists in the state from 2025 .
the way we pay these taxes will change .
the technology is there .
the initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund , which is funded from the taxes paid by U.S. dollars at the Zapfsäule , is bust .
but in America , no more is danced as much as before .
cars consume less petrol .
the government oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon ( less than 4 euro cents per litre ) has not risen for 20 years .
politicians do not dare to raise the tax by a penny at high fuel prices .
&quot; the petrol tax is just not sustainable , &quot; Lee Munnich , an expert on transport legislation at the University of Minnesota , said .
his state has recently equipped 500 cars with driver drivers to test a miles @-@ based pay system .
&quot; this represents the most sensible alternative in the long term , &quot; he said .
bureaucrats call it a miles @-@ based user fee .
it is not surprising that the idea is resonating with urban liberals , because the tax could , for example , be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate @-@ friendly exhaust gases are reduced .
California planners are relying on the system to develop strategies to achieve the ambitious , legally anchored goals of the federal government on climate change .
but Republican Bill Shuster from Pennsylvania , chairman of the House Transportation Committee , has also said he sees it as the most viable long @-@ term alternative .
the free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also tempted by the idea of having drivers pay for their return route .
&quot; this is not a tax that disappears in a black hole , &quot; explains Adrian Moore , vice president for guidelines at Reason .
people pay directly for what they get .
the move is also backed by two former American transport ministers who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move toward miles @-@ based billing .
the U.S. Senate approved a $ 90 million pilot project last year that would have included 10,000 cars .
but the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the offense , responding to the concerns of MPs from rural areas representing people who often have to move many miles on their way to work or town in everyday life .
several states and major cities are nevertheless moving in this direction .
the most committed is Oregon , which currently acquires 5,000 drivers for the country &apos;s largest experiment .
these drivers will soon pay the mileage fees instead of the petroleum tax to the state .
Nevada has already completed a pilot project .
new York City is also considering such a thing .
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks .
and the I @-@ 95 coalition , which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the East Coast ( including Maryland , Pennsylvania , Virginia and Florida ) , is currently investigating how to introduce the change .
the concept is not a universal hit .
in Nevada , where 50 volunteers were recently fitted with the devices , motorists were skeptical about the idea the government could pursue any of its movements .
&quot; concerns about Big Brother and such things were a big problem , &quot; explains Alauddin Khan , head of strategic and earnings management at Nevada &apos;s Department of Transportation .
people didn &apos;t want it .
when the test started , Nevada &apos;s ACLU warned on its website : &quot; it would be relatively easy to turn the tachograph into grown @-@ up surveillance devices . &quot;
there is no need to build a gigantic , bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals .
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology with which the state can capture the driven kilometres , but not exactly when and where .
with that , Khan said , the public would also be more reassured .
the hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California .
the company originally did not step in to help states tax motorists .
rather , it was their goal to take root in an emerging market for car insurance , where drivers are to pay on the basis of the driven miles .
but the devices it tested are also interesting for road planners , because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information regularly uploaded by modem .
&quot; people are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded , &quot; explained Ryan Morrison , managing director of True Mileage .
major mistakes have been made in some of these public pilot programmes .
there are far cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this .
in Oregon , planners are experimenting with giving motorists a number of choices .
you can choose a device with or without GPS .
or they choose no device at all and instead pay a lump sum fee based on the miles travelled by all residents of the state .
other bodies hope to sell the concept of a suspicious public by providing the devices with more functions than with few .
in New York City , transport officials want to develop a tax device with which parking charges can also be paid , insurance must only be paid for driven kilometres and speed data from other vehicles in real time , allowing motorists to avoid congestion .
&quot; motorists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits the system offers , &quot; said a planning document from the city .
however , some transport planners wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction .
at the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area , officials said Congress could simply solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by raising fuel tax .
an additional one @-@ off fee or annual levy could be imposed on motorists using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol , so that they too pay a fair share .
&quot; there is no reason for surgery if an aspirin is enough , &quot; explains Randy Rdefler , the head of legislation and public affairs at the commission .
if we do , hundreds of millions of motorists worry about their privacy and numerous other things .
