Council targets track equipment
should the railway crossing &quot; Am Hirschen &quot; be extensively rebuilt to increase traffic safety ?
yes , the local councils have decided .
for this , Schiltach must take in EUR 220 000 .
Deutsche Bahn intends to improve the Kinzigtal railway line next year .
in particular , safety at railway crossings is to be increased - regular collisions of trains with other vehicles occur nationwide .
if communities agree to the reconstruction measures , they must participate with a third in the cost , the rest share rail and the federal government .
Schiltach city builder Roland Grießerin explained to the local council the specifics of the &quot; Am Hirschen . &quot;
there , the city plans to build an outlet at the height of the tunnel in the west of the railway line .
larger vehicles , such as those transporting Langholz , could also stand in counter @-@ traffic , without having to block the tracks .
Greek farmers therefore proposed to construct a necessary base wall to allow the city to widen the subsequent road in due course to ensure a smooth flow of traffic .
this was controversially discussed in the local council as some councils questioned the need for street proliferation : Thomas Kipp , with his statement , brought critics &apos; mood to the point : &quot; do we have to take so much money because of so few vehicles ? &quot;
Mayor Thomas Haas echoed : the railway crossing &quot; Hirschen &quot; is regularly used for landing gear .
even wood from the &quot; Kuhbach &quot; area is partly transported across this route because up to 20 meters long vehicles could not use the track at the Häberlesbrücke because they could not turn into the main road .
in addition , the track dived as a redirection for those vehicles that are not allowed to use the tunnel when the main road is closed , Haas argued .
it is clear that Kirchberg and Schlossbergtunnel would have to be rebuilt and reconstructed , as is currently the case in Wolfach , that the railway crossing &quot; Am &quot; Hirschen &quot; could also be important for a longer period of time .
the councils agreed to investigate what costs would cause the planned broadening of the road .
despite this , a majority of people agreed to the conversion of the railway route , provided that the necessary support wall was built in such a way that the city could extend the subsequent road towards &quot; Bahnhofstraße &quot; to around 5.5 metres if necessary .
on the other hand , the conversion of the railway route to Gerberei Trautwein could lead to a very different problem , which concerns access to the rapidly rising &quot; Geroltzhäuser Way . &quot;
the administration had been investigating the railway &apos;s conversion plans from the engineering firm Breinlinger as it had doubts about whether the planned connection of the Geroltzhäuser Wegs would be possible without further notice .
the investigation concluded that it was not possible to exclude that the road &apos;s inclement conditions could lead to longer vehicles sitting up .
the city is responsible for this .
the restructuring could therefore result in liability disputes .
since both the logging and the bending worked in the current state of construction , you should not agree to the conversion of the railway , Haas argued .
at this point , too , the risk of collision of the train with a vehicle on the transition is significantly lower than at the other railway crossings , because it is directly next to the halfpoint center to which there is good visibility .
even trains from the main railway station would have to be slowed down at this point to the extent that no collision was threatening .
a majority of people refused to restructure this route because the city of Schiltach would have to &quot; bathe &quot; the problem with stationary vehicles , the councils said , as the railway could withdraw from responsibility after the construction works were completed .
as unproblematic , the panel considers the conversions to the &quot; Before Heubach &quot; and &quot; Before Kuhbach , &quot; for which cross @-@ border agreements have already been reached by rail .
ESA decides on big space missions : missions for billions
distance planets , gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch over the next few years .
thirty proposals were available and five are still in the race .
distance Worlds .
more than 1,000 planets at other stars have already found astronomers .
whether there is life at least on some of them , no one knows .
the selection is difficult : should you look for gravitational waves ?
or rather explore the origin of the cosmos ?
or , after Earth @-@ like planets , and perhaps discover alien life ?
these are the questions that the European Space Agency is responsible for .
for their Cosmic Vision programme , they are looking for ideas for two major space projects to make research a decisive contribution .
the budget for such &quot; L missions &quot; is approximately EUR 1 billion each .
the launch is expected to be 2028 and 2034 .
at the beginning of September , the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions .
thirty ideas were under discussion , and five of them have now come to the closer election .
many bodies understand the proposals , while researchers are concerned .
in the next few days , a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee .
a total of four major questions have been selected by the Esa , on which the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme launched in 2007 should be answered .
what are the conditions for the emergence of planets and lives ?
the exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and hence the emergence of planets that surround these stars - are still in the proverbial dark .
a large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this dark .
and if a star has planets , under what circumstances can life emerge there ?
in order to address this issue , the space telescope &quot; Cheops &quot; is to be launched in 2017 , with 500 already known planetary systems in our near vicinity .
however , the possibilities are limited , Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros .
with larger instruments , astronomers could map Earth @-@ like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus search for &quot; biomarkers &quot; : gases considered to be an indication of biological activity .
how does the solar system work ?
this question , too , is ultimately intended to clarify the conditions for the creation of life .
a key role is the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field , as well as the particle radiation it produces with the planetary system .
in our solar system , these processes can be examined in an exemplary manner .
with the Solar Orbiter , the Esa has already approved a M @-@ class mission ( where the budget is about half a billion euros ) for this issue .
the probe is expected to launch in 2017 and closely monitor the sun &apos;s surface and activity .
of great interest to researchers are Jupiter and his moon .
they want to find out what role the giant planet played in developing the solar system .
for this , the Esa provides the first of the three L missions of the Cosmic Vision program .
the probe &quot; Juice &quot; ( Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer ) is expected to begin its journey in 2022 .
eight years later , she reaches Jupiter to study the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moon of Europe , KALLISTO and Ganymed .
what are the fundamental physical laws of the universe ?
the world offers many ways to study subject matter under extreme conditions and to examine whether the natural laws we know are still valid there .
perhaps there are also deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory under which all known natural laws can be combined .
how did the universe emerge and what is there ?
13.7 billion years ago , our cosmos emerged through the Big Bang .
in addition to the subject we are familiar with , stars , planets and creatures like us , there is Dark matter , whose gravity is holding galaxies and galaxy clusters together , and Dark Energy , which accelerates the expansion of the world .
so far , researchers do not know what physical laws were valid in the first seconds of the Big Bang , nor what dark matter and dark energy exist .
with &quot; Euclid , &quot; the Esa has already approved an M mission to launch 2020 .
with a special telescope , the probe is intended to examine the distribution of the matter in the universe for the first time throughout the sky , thus allowing for references to the nature of Dunkler matter and Dunkler energy .
who could make the race
of the 30 proposals , only two will remain at the end of the selection process .
according to many experts , &quot; E @-@ Lisa , &quot; an ambitious concept for detecting gravitational waves , has the best chance of obtaining an L mission .
among them , physicists understand changes in the structure of space time that Albert Einstein predicted nearly 100 years ago .
they have not yet been proven .
Elisa could create that , the scientists hope behind the project .
the mission provides for one out of two or three probes existing detector stationed in space .
in contrast to plants on Earth , he could also prove gravitational waves that arose during the Big Bang , providing new insights into the evolution of the cosmos .
four other proposals still compete for the second L mission : a large X @-@ ray laboratory called &quot; Athena , &quot; which is to explore black holes among other things , &quot; Icy Planets , &quot; another mission to the outer planets of the solar system , &quot; Prism , &quot; is to investigate a mission to measure cosmic background radiation , and &quot; Finlandes . &quot;
there are already proposals for the transport of samples from Mars , for the exploration of moon , Venus and asteroids and for solar physics .
Snowden ready to &quot; cooperate &quot; with Germany on US surveillance
Edward Snowden , the whistleblower of the US intelligence service , has said he is willing to travel to Berlin and testify before the German Bundestag if the American National Security Agency and its director Keith Alexander do not provide answers about their activities .
German MP Hans @-@ Christian Flubele met Snowden on Thursday in Russia , where he received asylum to discuss the statement in Germany .
in a letter from Snowden presented to the media in Berlin on Friday , he writes : &quot; even though the outcome of my efforts was demonstrably positive , my government continues to treat a dissenting opinion as a filibuster and tries to criminalise political expression with criminal threat in which no defense is possible . &quot;
but to say the truth is not a crime .
in the letter , Snowden writes that he is convinced that the international community &apos;s support could convince the American government to drop the charge against him .
the charges filed by the U.S. Department of Justice include espionage and theft of state property .
