NSA declares that an &quot; internal error &quot; and not hackers are to blame for the crash of the site
the shadowy National Security Agency said late Friday that a mistake paralysed its public website for a few hours and not hackers , as claimed online .
&quot; NSA.gov was unavailable for some hours this night as an internal error occurred during a planned update , &quot; the spy agency explained in an e @-@ mail message .
the problem will be fixed this evening .
the claim that the breakdown was caused by a distributed denial of service attack ( DDoS ) is not true .
in the early evening hours , online server trackers noticed that the NSA website was unreachable for at least six hours and this remains unavailable to some users .
earlier , a spokesman for the NSA told ABC News that the authority &apos;s sensitive internal network was &quot; in no way compromised . &quot;
secret information is not in danger , according to the spokesman .
at least one group of hacking activists took charge of paralyzing the NSA website with a DDoS attack .
in case of such attacks , the target website is flooded with page calls until the servers are overloaded and the site collapses .
cybertactics are relatively simple and the attacks do not serve to penetrate the internal network of the target system .
the former supersecret NSA , whose nickname was once No Such Agency ( No such authority ) , now finds itself in the bright light of the public and looks after the revelations in recent months about its extensive surveillance program at home and abroad - a result of the secret NSA NSA data released by Edward .
the growing controversy surrounding the intelligence service sparked initial speculation that the incident today was the result of a targeted cyber operation .
