cocaine @-@ dependent lawyer who warned drug boss against police investigation must go to prison
Basharat Ditta , 42 , gave information to underworld figure Neil Scarborough
the lawyer was afraid his home drug addiction could come to light
he was sentenced by Liverpool Crown Court to three years in prison
a well @-@ known criminal defender who warned a drug baron against a major police investigation because he was afraid his secret drug addiction could be revealed has been sentenced to three years in prison .
Basharat Ditta , 42 , provided underworld figure Neil Scarborough with sensitive information about his activities in drug trafficking after being compromised by his own cocaine addiction .
the lawyer , hailed by criminalists as a &quot; first @-@ class &quot; lawyer with the nickname &quot; Bash , &quot; was arrested in his house in 2011 after police monitored Scarborough , whom he had represented in an earlier drug trial .
officials watched as Scarborough ( 32 ) delivered three bags of cocaine at the attorney &apos;s home in Blackburn , Lancashire , while he was with colleagues at a dinner of the Bar Association .
the investigation revealed that Ditta regularly consumed Class A drugs after traces of cocaine were found in his hair , on his wallet and on credit cards .
over an eight @-@ month period between January and August 2011 , he tried to obtain unauthorized information about the arrest of two men on behalf of Scarborough and one of his partners .
all four suspects were then monitored by police as part of a major investigation into heroin and cocaine trafficking in Lancashire , Cumbria , Merseyside , Berkshire and West Yorkshire .
along with 32 other people , they were later arrested after police secured heroin and cocaine worth £ 1.5 million as well as £ 200,000 in cash during a series of house searches .
ditta , 42 , gave information to the criminals because he feared his drug addiction could be publicised .
today Ditta , who works for the firm Forbes Solicitors in Blackburn , was found guilty and convicted at Liverpool Crown Court after a three @-@ week trial in two charges of obstruction of justice .
he admitted cocaine possession at an earlier survey .
the lawyer was transferred after police found out in their investigation into Scarborough that he had been in regular telephone contact with Ditta in February 2011 .
two investigators followed the suspect and saw how he went to Ditta &apos;s house and put the drugs there with a purity of 60 percent in a black golf glove under the attorney &apos;s garbage .
shortly after he delivered the drugs , Scarborough regularly telephoned Ditta , who was at the Blackburn Rovers football stadium in Ewood Park at dinner .
the lawyer returned home , took the drugs and then exchanged nine communications between the two .
in court , it became known that Ditta was a &quot; regular consul &quot; of cocaine after drugs from Class A were discovered in his hair , his wallet and on his credit cards .
ditta was later arrested but denied taking cocaine and said he had spoken to the alleged dealer because he was his client , claiming that her discussion was subject to &quot; legal secrecy . &quot;
during his arrest , Ditta took his wallet and tried to remove a number of credit cards , but they were assured and he was taken out of a hair sample .
at the police interrogation , he admitted that he entered an office and clients at home for legal matters , both under his private address and in the workplace .
in court , it was announced that he had called key players in the drug trade , some of which he had previously represented , after significant arrests and informed what investigators knew about them .
prosecutor Anne Whyte said : &quot; a criminal justice lawyer should know better than anyone else that you don &apos;t break the law . &quot;
ditta is accused of abuse of his position as a criminal defender as he has been too involved with certain clients .
the relationship in question is not simply that of a drug dealer , but a drug dealer who supplies his lawyer with drugs .
part of his communications was undoubtedly legitimate , because he was the lawyer of those people .
but that went far beyond the limits of a normal relationship between lawyer and client .
he acted as much as possible to the police investigation so that they could continue to investigate their criminal activities .
Mr Ditta brought his profession into disrepute .
he was too close to certain clients , particularly Scarborough , and he allowed his independence to be compromised .
ditta dismissed any wrongdoing and claimed , &quot; If I were a corrupt lawyer , what I &apos;m not , and wanted to pass on information to Scarborough , then I wouldn &apos;t wait 15 hours , but do that immediately . &quot;
but after the hearing , Superintendent Lee Halstead told police in Lancashire : &quot; Mr Ditta took the step from a criminal defense to a criminal at the moment when he began acquiring drugs from organized criminals . &quot;
his cocaine addiction led to hopeless compounding and made him susceptible to the motives of leading members of organised crime who instructed him to collect valuable information about police investigations .
lawyers must maintain the highest standards of integrity and ensure confidence and confidence in the public .
ditta has survived this trust and tried to hide behind the facade of his profession .
Lancashire &apos;s Serious and Organised Crime Unit launched the investigation into Ditta , which also led to a conviction in three cases because of the possession of cocaine and disability , underlining our determination to bring criminals to justice .
this case should be a warning to criminals and show that none can escape the arm of the law .
we find you and bring you to court .
Scarborough himself was sentenced to 14 years in prison after pleading guilty to conspiracy to heroin , cocaine and cannabis trafficking .
thirty @-@ five others involved in drug trafficking were sentenced to a total of 153 years for drug offences .
on his website , Ditta published an area of questions and answers about himself in which he admitted that his dream job was to represent clients in the death cell in America , his ultimate guest at dinner was Mohammed Ali and opportunity inequality was the motivation for his work .
