children &apos;s dreams become true
children &apos;s gardens and day @-@ care centres in the customs circle get mail these days .
the Black Forest Bote , in cooperation with Bauhaus and Sparkasse Zollernalb , wants to assist the facilities in realising their construction and refinement requirements .
does the kindergarten need a new sandbox ?
all children &apos;s gardens , day @-@ care centres and crèches from all over the customs circle can participate in the action .
if you have a wish to build or relax , you can apply for it with the Black Forest Boten .
be creative with your children and surprise the jury of Action Kindergarten @-@ Baustelle .
a jury consisting of representatives of Black Forest Bote , Bauhaus and Sparkasse Zollernalb selects three wishes from all submissions .
what are the conditions for participation ?
the wish should be realized with construction material worth a maximum of EUR 2000 and on a day ( action ) .
in addition , the winner himself must provide many hard @-@ working builders .
what about the day of action and the helpers ?
Bauhaus provides the material with the support of Sparkasse Zollernalb .
it will be delivered to the nursery on the agreed day and will then be processed directly by the helpers .
helpers can be parents , grandparents , friends , clubs and , of course , the educators and children themselves .
Kenyan press outraged by controversial media law
&quot; we are in a frightening situation and one may wonder : what does Parliament think of simply abolishing judicial independence tomorrow ? &quot; was read in the newspaper , which considers the draft law not unconstitutional .
&quot; the law is draconian and very criminal and we reject it , &quot; said Cyrus Kamau , managing director of Capital Group , which also includes CapitalFM , one of Kenya &apos;s most respected independent radio stations and news websites .
he said the new media tribunal &quot; will always be biased because it is an extended arm of government , &quot; and restrictions on content and advertising would damage Kenya &apos;s position in the global economy .
&quot; I hope the president listens to us and we appeal to him to reject this bill and return to Parliament , &quot; he said .
according to The Star newspaper , the government , through the new law , &quot; effectively takes the media into a stranglehold . &quot; by contrast , The Standard , Democracy and Freedom of speech in Kenya had suffered &quot; a serious blow , &quot; and labelled the draft as &quot; draconian . &quot;
the passage of the law is part of a series of measures aimed at strengthening national security in the aftermath of the attacks by armed Islamists on the Westgate shopping centre in September .
Kenyan media drew the anger of authorities because they released footage of security cameras on which to see the units sent to the scene allegedly robbed the luxury shopping centre .
police Chief David Kimaiyo responded with the hiring of two journalists and a leading media representative to interrogate , even if the pretrial was withdrawn after an outcry by the media .
under the new law , media houses can be fined up to 20 million Kenyan shields and individual journalists with up to one million and the further risk of losing their professional recognition or being excluded from official press accreditation .
the tribunal also has the right to confiscate the property of those affected if a penalty is not paid .
according to the Daily Nation , &quot; already a single penalty can push most radio stations into bankruptcy . &quot;
in addition , the newspaper believes these measures could have a devastating effect on that of its description of &quot; vibrant blogosphere &quot; Kenya .
if they were to silence the media , politicians could do unpunished whatever they want .
&quot; no one will ever know , &quot; wrote Mutuma Mathiu , a journalist at the nation who calls the Kenyan media a crucial control factor in public life .
&quot; leave politicians themselves , lead the country into bankruptcy and return us to the time of hunters and collectors , &quot; he commented .
Kenyan lawmakers have already attracted public anger in the past .
in May , they voted to reverse the cuts imposed by the National Compensation Commission and reinstated their defective salaries of about 532,000 chilling tax @-@ free per month - they are among the highest in the world .
