security concerns in Mozambique grow amid clashes between influential figures
thousands of people gathered in central Maputos under the watchful eyes of the statue of Samora Machel , the state founder and first president of Mozambique , to agree to peace calls at a rare public demonstration .
&quot; we want peace again , we want stability , &quot; said Vanessa de Sousa , managing director of an investment firm .
fearing for the future of the country , she swapped her business clothes against a T @-@ shirt with the inscription &quot; We demand security &quot; in Portuguese and joined the crowd at the capital &apos;s Independence Square on Thursday .
for two weeks , there have been almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and RENAMO , which are among the worst fighting since the peace agreement over 20 years ago .
RENAMO was once a notorious rebel movement , initially backed by the White @-@ ruled Rhodesia and later the apartheid government of South Africa in an effort to destabilize the country &apos;s independent government .
after the 1992 peace treaty , she became an opposition party .
analysts believe it is unlikely that the country will fall back into a widening conflict , but recent events have worried foreign investors and locals .
much is at stake for the fast @-@ growing economy , because the discovery of vast gas reserves off the coast and coal miners in the northwest could bring investment of more than $ 50 billion from companies like Rio Tinto , Vale from Brazil , Eni from Italy and Anadarko from the US over the next few years .
the ruling Frelimo party , the dominant force since 1975 , and RENAMO blame each other for the tensions .
RENAMO claims the government has provoked recent clashes by attacking its members in the province of Sofala , a traditional stronghold of Renamos , on October 17 .
the assaults on the former rebels escalated when government forces attacked RENAMO bases and tried to kill Afonso Dhlakama , the group &apos;s leader , Renamos spokesman told the Financial Times .
the government blames RENAMO for the clashes and accuses the organization of attacking soldiers .
President Armando Guebuza has sought to downplay concerns about instability .
speaking to AFP , the French news agency , he said Wednesday that Dhlakama considers himself a &quot; loser &quot; who &quot; wants to use all his remaining forces to prove he can impose his decisions on the government . &quot;
both Frelimo and RENAMO stress that they want to avoid war .
but concerns have increased since Mazanga was quoted as saying RENAMO issued the 1992 peace agreement .
he explained to the FT that he meant that Frelimo would no longer respect the agreement .
&quot; our vision is to resume negotiations and be serious , &quot; Mazanga said .
previous talks between the parties have contributed little to resolving the tensions that have been fueled by a series of clashes this year .
&quot; we have here two adult men ( Guebuza and Dhlakama ) who come together the heads , &quot; says Joseph Hanlon , a lecturer at Open University and Mozambique expert .
none of them is good at negotiating and none is prepared to make the necessary concessions .
RENAMO , which is pushing for election reforms , has already said it will boycott the local elections in November .
presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year .
some commentators have interpreted the use of force as an attempt by a ailing movement to obtain concessions and financial benefits from the government .
Renamos electoral success has been shrinking since 1992 , while a newer party founded by a former RENAMO member will probably improve in the elections .
Mazanga claims that Guebuza - whose resignation is due when his second term ends next year - wants to destroy the country &apos;s democracy .
&quot; he doesn &apos;t want multi @-@ party democracy , he doesn &apos;t want transparent elections , he doesn &apos;t want peace because he doesn &apos;t want to give up the presidential office , &quot; Mazanga said .
it is unclear what capacity RENAMO has , but it has taken unrest inciting attacks on police stations and vehicles on a major North @-@ South link .
most of the fighting took place in the province of Sofala , which lies a few hundred kilometres north of Maputo , but where Beira is located , the port , the mining companies such as Rio Tinto and Vale to export coal .
in June , Rio broke a month to use the railroad after RENAMO announced an attack on the track .
Mazanga responded cautiously to the question of whether RENAMO will repeat that threat .
RENAMO wanted to &quot; warn the international community that things are not good in Mozambique , &quot; Mazanga said .
instability has boosted frustration over the government , says Fernando Lima , head of Mediacoop , an independent media company , because many people have already been caused by corruption , sluggish progress in development and a recent abduction wave .
&quot; people think the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country and he should be the one who finds solutions to the problems , &quot; he explains .
Omar Sultane , a demonstrator , said people just wanted stability .
&quot; no one interested RENAMO and Frelimo , they just want peace and usable roads again , &quot; he explained .
children should be taught myths and legends as &quot; models for life , &quot; according to an author .
Thor &apos;s stories showed that &quot; brutal force has no chance against clever tricks , &quot; and the Artus legend demonstrates how important it is to have a dream .
many of the myths , however , are &quot; far too wild , too offensive and in some cases too dirty to be taught in schools , &quot; which is why Crossley @-@ Holland argued for a &quot; careful selection &quot; of age @-@ appropriate works .
&quot; I find it wonderful that in America myths and folklore are already part of education , &quot; he said .
I have proposed this for twenty years as a plan .
he added that in authors and teachers who are &quot; overly didactic , &quot; children would be &quot; completely shut off &quot; because in entertaining stories , the messages would be &quot; subdued . &quot;
Crossley @-@ Holland , who has translated Beowulf from the Angels and is author of the Penguin Book of Norse Myths and the British Folk Tales , explained : &quot; you can pursue certain intentions , but you should keep them in the background as possible . &quot;
perhaps the biggest difference between an adult author who writes for adults , and an author who writes for children , lies in the need to convey hope .
not everything needs to be simplified or led to the Happy End , but there is an immanent sense of good and evil .
this must be understated , revealed by history and not explained .
this is the old story of the moment rather than narrative .
