Ben Greenman : ten Years New York Comedy Festival : the New Yorker
one could say that New York City is the birthplace of stand @-@ up comedy in America : just a hundred years ago , the varietologist Frank Fay , who worked as a Conférencier at the Palace Theatre on Broadway , began telling the crowd straight jokes in the form of a conversation .
over the years , Fays innovation has been expanded , just as last at the New York Comedy Festival .
launched and directed by Caroline Hirsch , the founder of stand @-@ up institution Carolines , this year &apos;s festival celebrates its 10th anniversary with over sixty shows in small clubs and major theaters .
&quot; most of these headliners began at Carolines and then became increasingly successful until they were at some point known to compete in a club , &quot; Hirsch said .
we designed this festival so that we can continue to work with them .
this year &apos;s event includes performances by Wanda Sykes , Kathy Griffin and Bill Maher , as well as &quot; Stand Up for Heroes , &quot; an annual music and comedy charity event for army veterans at Madison Square Garden , where Bruce Springsteen , Jon Stewart , Roger Waters and Bill perform .
with the festival , the world of comedy has grown as well .
a number of comedians attending this year &apos;s festival have become aware of more unconventional ways , such as broadcasts on smaller television channels such as Comedy Central , FX and Spike .
Nick Kroll became known with a sitcom on cable television ( the ironic @-@ sounding fantasy football series &quot; The League &quot; on FXX ) and now has his own sketch show on Comedy Central .
Jenny Slate was part of the cast at &quot; Saturday Night Live &quot; as well as &quot; Parks and Recreation , &quot; although she is best known for her viral video series &quot; Marcel the Shell with Shoes On . &quot;
both Kroll and Slate and other young comedians with characteristic voices ( the surreal pessimistic Anthony Jeselnik , the ironic , focused on racial issues W. Kaumau Bell ) are products of the decentralised world of American comedy .
one of the festival &apos;s biggest visitor magnets is an interview : David Steinberg speaks with Larry David .
Steinberg began as a stand @-@ up comedian but has become a respected television and film director as well as an unofficial comedy historian .
from 2005 to 2007 he moderated a television programme entitled &quot; Sit Down Comedy with David Steinberg &quot; at TV Land .
the meeting will take place in the Town Hall in the middle of Manhattan .
&quot; the city is definitely in the comedy DNA of Larry &apos;s entire work , &quot; Steinberg said .
he told me if he is here , he sometimes goes through the alley between two buildings and thinks : hey , if I lose all my money , then maybe I live here .
