Court blocks decision on NYPD &apos;s Stop @-@ and @-@ Frisk Directive
a federal appeals court in the U.S. blocked the order of a judge on Thursday calling for changes to the stop @-@ and @-@ risk program ( &quot; stop and search &quot; ) of the New York Police Department , and stripped the judge of the case .
the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said Judge Shira Scheindlin &apos;s decisions would be suspended until a city &apos;s appeal was decided .
the judge ruled in August that the city violated the constitution with the way the program is implemented for the holding and questioning of people .
the city appealed against its assessment and the remedies requested , including the decision to set up a monitoring body to assist the police in amending their directive and training programmes .
the Court of Appeals heard the arguments on the required suspension on Tuesday .
the Appeal Report stated that the judge must be stripped of the case as it violated the code of conduct for U.S. judges by determining that a judge should avoid the appearance of partisanship ; this was partly based on a series of media interviews and public statements in which it had publicly responded to the court &apos;s criticism .
the judge had ruled that police officers violated the civil rights of tens of thousands of people because they inappropriately targeted black and Latin American men with the stop @-@ and @-@ risk program .
it appointed an external body to monitor the implementation of major changes , including reforms to guidelines , training and service supervision , and ordered a pilot program with cameras trapped on the body in neighborhoods where most controls were carried out .
in August , the city of New York agreed to end the practice of storing names and addresses of people who were released after a check by police .
an oral trial to appeal the city is scheduled after March 14 , 2014 .
the stop @-@ and @-@ risk tactic has been criticised by a number of civil rights advocates .
controls of this kind have been in different forms for decades , but the number of checks recorded during the term of nonpartisan mayor Michael Bloomberg rose to an all @-@ time high of 684,330 in 2011 , most of them black and Latin American men .
in 2004 , four men belonging to all minorities filed a lawsuit that turned into a collection box .
supporters of changes to the NYPD &apos;s stop @-@ and @-@ risk program say the changes will end unfair practices and create a more trustworthy and effective police force , as well as influence the way other police chiefs use the scheme .
opponents believe the changes would dampen the morale of the police , but not crime ; nor would money be wasted and the broader problem of a police force under pressure after the removal of thousands of bodies in the last decade .
the judge pointed out that they do not end the stop @-@ and @-@ risk practice , which is constitutional , but only the way the checks are implemented by the NYPD reformed .
