James clapper , U.S. Director of National Intelligence , again insisted in September that the U.S. did not use foreign espionage options &quot; to steal the operating secrets of foreign companies on behalf of U.S. companies so that they could expand their international competitiveness or profit . &quot;
but since Edward Snowden , the former employee who became a whistleblower , began publishing his filling horns to U.S. surveillance secrets , European governments and business chiefs are no longer sure if they can take the director at the word .
reports that the American National Security Agency is spiking Brazilian oil company Petrobas and collecting data from American cloud providers including Google and Yahoo have brought the company paranoia to a new peak because of government surveillance .
the barrel to overrun brought the revelation that Chancellor Angela Merkel &apos;s phone had vanished , possibly for 10 years .
if the most powerful person in Europe can target , then corporate governance is certainly potential targets .
Snowden has made intensive cooperation between U.S. intelligence and business transparent .
I think it is conceivable that these data will be used for mutual benefit .
&quot; Germany must wake up , &quot; explains Oliver Green , president of BITMi , which represents small and medium @-@ sized IT companies in Germany .
German companies believe the US now poses an almost as high risk as China when it comes to industrial espionage and data theft , according to a survey published in July by the consulting firm EY .
however , in the documents leaked by Snowden , there has so far been no evidence that the US has passed on the operating secrets of foreign companies to its own companies .
politicians have expressed concern that the EU lacked certain IT and Internet opportunities and should reduce its dependence on the US .
companies are sceptical about this .
in the Bundestag it was suggested that we should build a German Google .
I can only close my eyes and slowly reopen them ...
&quot; that &apos;s not working , &quot; says Hasso Plattner , chairman of German software maker SAP .
if we had wanted a strong European IT industry , we should not have let it die 20 years ago .
everything in Germany is subsidised , from coal to cars to agriculture .
everything , except the IT industry .
still , reach and technical sophistication of US spy agencies uncovered by the Snowden revelations have shocked firms that had previously seen the largest spy risk in China .
there is a major change in cloud computing , because European business leaders are now more aware that data stored in the United States is subject to jurisdiction and are therefore potentially at risk .
according to a survey conducted by the Cloud Security Alliance , a trade institution , after revelations about U.S. data mining activities with Prism shed about 10 percent of non @-@ U.S. members &apos; plans to use an American provider .
Jim Snabe , deputy managing director of SAP , says : &quot; we see a new question from customers that didn &apos;t exist a year ago - it is : where are my data stored and can you guarantee that these will remain physically in this legal area ? &quot;
many German business leaders believe that recent reports simply confirm what they already knew , namely that powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets and that they must therefore be guarded at all costs .
it is no surprise that economic espionage is taking place .
that has always been the case .
&quot; it has been an issue for many years and has not fundamentally changed by the current discussion , &quot; says Kurt Bock , chairman of chemical company BASF .
Americans spy on us at commercial and industrial level , just as we do , because it is in the national interest to defend our businesses .
the management does not normally discuss the counter @-@ measures taken , because this gives an advantage to attackers .
in large companies , employees have long been told that taking a free USB stick at a fair or keeping a laptop in the hotel room is not advisable , to say the least .
Ulrich Hackenberk , chief executive at automaker Audi , says it has been part of standard practice for years before a board meeting to collect the phones so that they cannot be used as interception devices .
the German BVT advises executives to use simple prepaid phones when they go on overseas trips because smartphones may be compromised .
prepaid phones are thrown away afterwards .
there is concern , however , that small and medium @-@ sized enterprises remain vulnerable to hacking and surveillance .
in Germany , many of these companies are world leaders in their respective niches .
&quot; small and medium @-@ sized businesses often lack the experience , staff and financial resources to effectively protect operating secrets against unauthorized access , &quot; the BVT warns in a report .
the US warns its own firms against economic espionage by other countries .
according to Washington Post , the U.S. National Intelligence Estimate in February ordered France , Russia and Israel behind China to rank two of the countries that used to obtain economic data from the hacking .
a board member of a German blue @-@ chip company agreed when it comes to economic espionage , then &quot; the French are the worst . &quot;
