CDC release allergic lines for schools
on Wednesday , the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention ( CDC ) released a series of guidelines for dealing with food allergies from children in schools .
these are the first such directives issued by the US government as the number of schoolchildren with food allergies increases .
one in 20 children in the United States now has a food allergy .
the spread of food allergies among children has increased by 18 percent between 1997 and 2007 , according to the CDC .
the guidelines provide information for schools to raise awareness among teachers and staff of food allergies and how to deal with children showing allergic reactions .
it is also recommended that schools have Epinephrin pretending - the auto injection of the EpiPen brand is most commonly used - to confront a potentially deadly oversensitivity response .
lawmakers in the states have recently changed the rules so that schools can easily pre @-@ empt Epinephrin .
the report also includes a list of typical symptoms called by children who have an allergic reaction .
children might say , &quot; It feels as if something is pressed on my tongue , &quot; &quot; My tongue feels as if a hair is on it &quot; or &quot; my tongue crippling . &quot;
parents of intersex children can choose &apos; gender undetermined &apos;
Germany is the first European nation to recognise a third gender for children born with unambiguous genitals .
newborns are no longer given rigid male or female .
under the new law , parents no longer have to declare sex for such children , but can specify &quot; undetermined &quot; or &quot; not defined &quot; on birth certificate .
the aim of the law is to take advantage of parents &apos; pressure to ensure they do not have to make rushed decisions regarding surgery for a sex assignment in newborns , and to combat discrimination against intersexual people .
an intersexual person said , according to the BBC years later , &quot; I &apos;m neither man nor woman . &quot;
I remain the patchwork created by doctors , mutilated and full of scars .
it is estimated that one in 2,000 children every year are neither a boy nor a girl .
they are among the intersexes , a group that falls under the diagnosis of &quot; sexual differentiation disorder &quot; ( DSD ) , a collective term for people with atypical chromosomes , germ glands ( ovaries or testicles ) or unusually developed genitals .
Wallis Simpson was possibly intersexual .
the understanding of gender identification is still not very well developed , but most experts in the United States advise that we should use the best available information on gender assignment if a provision is not possible and not wait for the psychological and physical development of the child before deciding , if any , for an operation .
the New York psychiatrist Dr Jack Drescher , who specializes in the issue of gender identification , said the new German law &quot; captures after a good thing . &quot;
intersexual children pose an ethical dilemma .
&quot; some people have life @-@ threatening illnesses that require surgery , but for most children this does not apply , &quot; he said .
you can do a sexual assignment without surgery and then wait to see how identity develops .
the scientific data on how a child develops its gender identity at all is not very accurate .
no one knows why it is happening .
it &apos;s like the mystery of why people are gay .
a 2011 report to the European Commission states that intersexual people should be distinguished from transsexual or transgender people , because their status is not gender @-@ based , but because of their biological constitution , which is neither exclusively male nor female , but typically defines both simultaneously or not clearly as one of them .
these characteristics were reflected in post @-@ secondary sexual characteristics such as muscle mass , acidification , breasts and stature , priority sexual characteristics such as reproductive organs and genitals , or chromosomes and hormones .
the report also provides an overview of discrimination faced by intersexual and transgender persons in professional life , as well as the extent of harassment , violence and prejudice .
boys who are not equal to the gender picture now have a special camp .
meanwhile , in Australia and Nepal it is possible for adults to indicate male , female or &quot; third sex &quot; on official documents .
in June , Australian Norrie May @-@ Welby ( 52 ) was recognized as the world &apos;s first &quot; gender @-@ free &quot; person after a court granted life @-@ long retention of an &quot; unspecified &quot; gender status .
in addition to M and W , German cards will have a third assignment , X for intersex , according to the Interior Ministry .
in neighboring France , sex issues are still controversial , according to a news statement on France 24 .
in 2011 , dozens of French lawmakers of the strictly Catholic country signed a petition saying &quot; gender theory &quot; should be removed from school books .
the US website Catholic Online has also opposed German law , saying : &quot; if the world is dragged into a new state where gender is a decision , but not sexual activity , then we are twisting two more pillars of civilisation . &quot;
the mother of a newborn from Maryland explained to Baby Zone she was better off when babies are assigned a gender at birth .
&quot; parents are already stressful enough even without further restrictions , especially if you don &apos;t know the gender of your own child , &quot; she told the parent website .
children need stability and security .
historically , children born both with male and female genitals were called hermaphrodites , according to the attractive Greek god who had both sexes .
ten years ago , medicine regarded sex as something that could be wiped out and then rebuilt .
but meanwhile , the ethical foundations of an operation are being questioned after it is now known how complex the gender identity is , and that doctors can also be wrong because they don &apos;t know how the child feels when growing up with the gender they allocate .
&quot; in the mid @-@ 20th century , you called this one , psychiatric emergencies , &quot; Drescher said .
when such a child was born , it was not the psychiatrist but the surgeon .
the ruling theory on the treatment of children with unambiguous genitals dates back to Dr. John Money from Johns Hopkins University , who considered that gender was formal .
he coined the term &quot; gender identity , &quot; arguing that social and environmental attacks - such as parents educate a child - interacted with a child &apos;s genes and hormones , preaching whether a person considers himself male or female .
but in a 1966 case known as &quot; John / Joan , &quot; his theories became controversial .
he advised the parents of a boy whose penis had been separated from a botched circumcision , completely castrating the child and also removing his testicles and then raising him as a girl .
&quot; money presented this case as a successful example of a transformation , but it wasn &apos;t , &quot; Drescher added .
when the boy was about 15 , he moved back to male sex and married a woman .
with 38 , though , he committed suicide .
according to Drescher , there are still doctors who would practice this model .
but in the 1990s , with the entry of the Internet , survivors of these sexual operations have resigned to the public who are &quot; not happy with the outcome . &quot;
for example , at Jim Bruce , a 36 @-@ year @-@ old author from Montana who was born with XY @-@ male chromosomes but ambiguous genitals .
doctors were not clear about whether he had a large clitoris or a small penis and were convinced he could never lead a &quot; satisfying life &quot; as a man .
so his external body and testicles were surgically removed shortly after the birth of 1976 and he was raised as a girl .
at age 12 , he received female hormones .
&quot; I knew I wasn &apos;t a girl , &quot; he explained to ABCNews.com
I was unhappy , but it was really hard to ask questions .
at age 18 , he should get a vaginal plastic .
but since he was depressed and knew something was wrong , he demanded his medical files .
what he found out was shocking .
I was sterilised at my birth - and none ever told me .
Bruce was born with a DSD through which his body could not produce enough testosterone to develop genitals .
after he learned the truth , he moved back to male identity , received testosterone injections and allowed his breasts to be removed .
through the operation , he has become infertile .
today , he fights for others in an organization called Interface Project for intersexual people to be perceived as normal .
but Anne Tamar @-@ Mattis , managing director of California @-@ based legal group Advocates for Informed Choice , is concerned that German law can &quot; encourage defamation and stigma . &quot;
&quot; many activists are concerned that the German decision could encourage parents to make quick decisions and allow the child not to be determined , &quot; she explained .
we fear this will encourage intervention .
we think it would be better to assign male or female sex and then wait to see it .
but we do not yet know how the law will affect it , so we can only speculate .
Tamar @-@ Mattis said her organization supports Australian law because &quot; it allows adults to recognise as a third sex . &quot;
&quot; adults should be able to make their own decisions about their legal sex , &quot; she explained .
German law is about assignment at birth .
this is not a struggle to force small children to do so .
if they are grown , they can decide on their own body .
but Dr. Arlene Baratz , a bruising scientist from Pittsburg who has a daughter with a sexual differentiation disorder and supports hundreds of others in a self @-@ help group , says German law &quot; empowers &quot; both parents and children .
Katie , the daughter of Baratz , was born with male chromosomes but has a DSD called complete android resistance .
because of the receptor defect of the target cells for testosterone , Katie developed female characteristics .
she has a vagina , but no uterus and no ovaries .
today , Katie is 29 and married ; she works at the University of Pennsylvania as an employee in child psychiatry .
while it is infertile , it hopes to get a child through adoption or a surrogate mother .
&quot; the law gives parents room , which means they don &apos;t have to rush decisions , &quot; Baratz said .
it gives them the time to do different tests and clarify things and gives them time before writing &quot; male &quot; or &quot; female . &quot;
in this way everything is fine - you pull the child big and love it .
you have a wonderful baby and enjoy the parenthood .
and you don &apos;t have to rush an operation that can &apos;t be reversed .
&quot; this includes the children in the decision with one and removes the fear that parents are pushing because they believe they would not do the right thing , &quot; she explained .
ultimately , the child decides on the sex that suits him better - and that &apos;s wonderful .
this will enable children to make the decision themselves .
