U.S. wants Snowden to continue prosecuting
the U.S. has not changed its stance on former U.S. intelligence worker Edward Snowden .
he is still accused of passing unauthorised secret information .
he must therefore face criminal proceedings in the US , the US State Department spokeswoman , Jennifer Psaki , said in Washington .
Snowden &apos;s recent remarks would not change that either .
before that , German Green politician Hans @-@ Christian Flubele appealed to the US after a meeting with Snowden in Moscow to avoid threatening him further with punishment .
Psaki stressed that currents concerned one parliamentarian rather than one German member of government .
intelligence Secretary Edward Snowden is in principle ready to meet with German authorities .
first , however , he wants to know his situation .
that made clear to the former NSA employee sought by the US in an unaddressed letter published by Green politician Hans @-@ Christian Flubele on Friday after a meeting with Snowden and passed on to the federal government , Bundestag and general counsel .
the letter , according to a translation published by currents , is as follows :
to the beneficiaries
I was asked to write to you about your inquiry into mass surveillance .
I called Edward Joseph Snowden and was previously contracted or employed by a direct order as a technical expert at the National Security Agency ( NSA ) , the Central Intelligence Agency ( CIA ) and the Defense Intelligence Agency ( DIA ) of the United States .
in the course of my work in these institutions , I witnessed systematic violations of the laws of my government , which led me to act on moral duty .
as a result of the publication of these concerns , I saw myself exposed to a serious and persistent hatred which forced me to leave my family and my home country .
I am currently living in exile and enjoying temporary asylum granted to me by the Russian Federation under international law .
I am encouraged by the response to my political action , both in the US and elsewhere .
citizens around the world , and also senior officials - including the United States - have judged the revelations to be a system of all @-@ encompassing surveillance that is not guilty of any accountability to anyone as a service to the public .
these espionage revelations drew many suggestions on new laws and guidelines aimed at previously covert abuses of public confidence .
the benefits for society from these findings are becoming increasingly clear , while at the same time the risks taken into account have been clearly reduced .
although the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive , my government continues to treat dissent as a filibuster , seeking to criminalise and prosecute political expression .
yet the truth is not a crime .
I am confident that the United States Government , with the support of the international community , will adopt this unacceptable position .
I hope that , if the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved , I will be able to participate in the responsible clarification of the facts concerning the statements made in the media , particularly in terms of the truth and authenticity of the reports .
I look forward to having a meeting with you in your country as soon as the situation is resolved and thank you for your efforts to uphold international law that protects us all .
Edward Snowden testifies by Hans @-@ Christian Flubele
