report : Obama campaign to replace Biden with Hillary Clinton
President Barack Obama &apos;s closest advisers have been considering replacing Vice President Joe Biden in the 2012 campaign with Hillary Clinton , according to the New York Times .
the revelation is the most notable surprise of Mark Halperin &apos;s long @-@ awaited work and John Heilemann on the 2012 campaign , &quot; Double Down : game Change 2012 . &quot;
the Times has a copy of the soon @-@ to @-@ be book and reported on Thursday night that the president &apos;s top advisers had conducted &quot; extensive group meetings and polls at the end of 2011 &quot; to find out whether it would be better for Obama &apos;s declining hope of re @-@ election if he dropped Biden .
according to Jonathan Martin , national political correspondent for the Times , the book thoroughly tracks the history of the efforts of leading campaign and White House staff , notably former White House chief of staff Bill Daley , to measure the effect it has on poll numbers to swap former Secretary Clinton against the vice president .
the potential change was a closely watched secret within the campaign infrastructure in Chicago and in the Oval Office .
only half a dozen of the president &apos;s closest advisers - including Daley , the former campaign manager of Obama , Jim Messina , and the White House &apos;s former senior adviser , David Axelrod and David Plouffe - knew about the planned change .
in &quot; Double Down , &quot; it is claimed that Daley was at the forefront of efforts to exchange Biden despite her &quot; close , personal relationship , &quot; before eventually deciding against such a move , after the data showed that Clinton &apos;s candidacy &quot; would not significantly improve Obama &apos;s chances . &quot;
in an interview with Martin , Daley confirmed that the government was actually considering replacing Biden with Clinton .
&quot; I said a whole series of things to consider , and that was one of them , &quot; Daley told the magazine .
one has to remember that the president had terrible poll numbers at the time , so we thought , &quot; To God &apos;s will , what are we doing ? &quot;
while Daley described the investigations as &quot; necessary care , &quot; Martin told Anderson Cooper of CNN that during the campaign for re @-@ election , significant efforts had been made to determine whether such a train would pay off in terms of the polls .
&quot; in campaigns , not so much money is spent on polls and focus groups unless you seriously think about something , &quot; Martin explained on AC360 .
but it &apos;s not clear whether Obama knew his team was thinking about an exchange .
Martin told CNN he asked Daley if his current boss had known about the potential change .
although Daley explained he did not believe the president was &quot; aware of the possible change , &quot; the former chief of staff admitted it was &quot; possible &quot; that Obama knew about it .
Martin added that &quot; Double Down &quot; did not provide a definitive answer to the question of whether the political explorations had reached Obama &apos;s desk .
Cooper asked Martin if he seriously thinks Obama knew nothing about the investigation into whether Biden should be dropped in the elections .
&quot; possible , &quot; Martin replied .
what happens to my e @-@ mail ?
e @-@ mail actually means electronic letter .
has e @-@ mail , similar to conventional mail , been technically implemented in the design of the Internet service ?
when designing early Internet services , the emphasis was on making communication possible .
as a result , the basic technical protocols did not ensure a stable foundation for an audible exchange of letters .
therefore , a conventional e @-@ mail corresponds more to an open postcard than a sealed letter .
if user sends &quot; Anna &quot; to &quot; Benni , &quot; are the computers of the two connected directly ?
Anna &apos;s e @-@ mail program or browser sends the mail to her service provider &apos;s mail server in the first step .
if she has a Gmail account , for example , that would be Google .
this mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses .
on the route , the mail can run through several other servers on the Internet .
Bennie can then call the content to his provider .
are conventional e @-@ mails on their way through the network ?
most mails are read several times by software robots .
the sender provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an appendix .
a virus check is also done on the receiver systems .
in addition , providers check whether it is a troublesome and unwelcome spam mail that is deleted immediately or at least sorted into a spam folder .
do the robots have another task ?
for systems such as GMail , the robot also identifies the information Google needs to place context advertising .
if Anna and Benni communicate via GMail about their upcoming holiday trip , Google can hide related links to holiday deals .
do unknown people also read the emails ?
the likelihood of unauthorized people reading a mail is extremely low .
in theory , however , that is possible .
in companies , administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail .
law enforcement and intelligence agencies also have legal means to intercept or take note of e @-@ mails .
this will result in possible illegal exit actions .
is it possible to protect emails against reading ?
with a encryption according to the OpenPGP standard , an email can be encrypted effectively against reading .
with great technical effort , it is also possible to conceal the metadata of e @-@ mail communication , so that it is not even possible to recognize who has communicated with whom .
how important are Yahoo and Google on the e @-@ mail market in Germany ?
for the mainly privately used post offices , Yahoo and Google play only a subordinate role , according to an investigation by Convios Consulting from August 2013 .
while Yahoo Mail &apos;s shares had recently fallen , GMail was able to clear from Google .
