George Kerevan : European unbundling gives Scots the choice
a new day , a new horror story on independence .
this time we are being warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership .
this provides the cue for stories about passport controls in Berwick and a border secured with barbed wire along the Hadrianswall .
indeed , the Strathclyde proposal pointed to the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe , but , as expected , this played no part in the headlines .
nor has anyone mentioned that EU member states often turn their back on strict rules when they are more favourable to them .
as Scotland does not currently belong to the Schengen area , the continued non @-@ respect for Brussels would be just a small concession in exchange for what is really wanted by the Scots .
so really no story .
and one that has already come in the years that it already resembles a fossil : the first time I &apos;ve heard the &quot; independence means passport controls &quot; duck at least 40 years ago .
an interesting point is lost in the constant recovery of this ancient history .
why do we expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe ?
why swap the London yoke against that of Brussels , especially now ?
these are the real European news : the great plan for the unification of Europe , drawn up after the war , has stalled .
with the euro crisis , the European project has officially died .
across the EU , parties gain ground that are hostile to the EU or want to throw the euro on board as a common currency .
even in Germany , the Eurosceptic Party was able to gain an alternative to Germany - only this year - almost five million votes in the federal election in September , effectively dropping the Free Democrats ( the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats ) out of the Bundestag .
there has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe .
however , the current economic crisis is emerging as a turning point .
because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank , combined with the straitjacket to which the national economy is coerced by holding onto the single currency , many people believe that the European project has gone too far .
the euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits - that was the case only in Greece .
instead , the Eurosystem has fixed its members at exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters - and that is what German politicians would like to leave .
without the possibility of devaluing the local currency , southern Europe finds itself again with a built @-@ in productivity disadvantage vis @-@ à @-@ vis Germany .
the only way is to cut wages and public spending - spurred by Berlin .
there is a deep European productivity problem behind the current budgetary and monetary problems .
as a result of the &quot; green &quot; energy guidelines imposed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry is paying double for electricity and four times for gas compared with the United States .
this is a crippling cost axe , as we could already see in Grangemouth .
all the world &apos;s wage rules do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas .
as a result , a revolt is drawing up , particularly in France , the EU &apos;s former cheerleader .
after the war , France &apos;s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and lift Paris to an equal footing with Washington .
but Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has pushed Europe into its own economic policy , which is struggling the struggling French economy .
the result is that Marine Le Pen &apos;s right @-@ wing , anti @-@ EU National Front has just won a crucial post @-@ election election , drawing the ruling Socialists to three .
the National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the vote - a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split on the right spectrum would automatically bring benefits to the left .
what does Le Pen do with her newly won popularity among the white French working class ?
it wants to use next year &apos;s EU elections to forge an anti @-@ EU , anti @-@ Community monetary bloc in the European Parliament .
if the anti @-@ EU parties do well in these elections - and this is very possible - then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament .
this is the point I want to make : in the not too distant future , the growing resentment of the EU and the single currency will be found together to abolish the euro .
the EU will not disappear , but it will become more like the &quot; Europe of the ( sovereign ) nations &quot; that General de Gaulle favored .
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may stick to the euro , but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies .
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of becoming part of the US .
however , Washington &apos;s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will be alone in the Atlantic rain .
where does Scotland stay with all this ?
we can decide to be a region of ( lately ) Klein @-@ England .
or we can defend our own economic interests - including telling Berlin and Brussels what they can put in place .
I suspect Scotland could go well in a looser European interconnection , provided we keep our own currency .
cooperation with other similar countries is easier in an unfederal Europe of nations .
otherwise , we should consider doing so with Norway and maintaining our economic independence .
the SNP government in Scotland is - remarkably - the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 because of the rejection of the proposed ( and anticipated ) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory @-@ Lib Dem coalition .
it would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now , only to have austerity imposed by Berlin and Brussels .
early puberty : growing faster
African @-@ American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers , as investigations show .
physical changes don &apos;t mean immediate puberty
there is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
experts believe the epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
the trend for early puberty is less pronounced among boys
former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in child health and family affairs .
should a mother be concerned if her daughter is already growing breasts and shamhairs aged seven or eight ?
at the annual conference of the Children &apos;s Medical Association American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando , Florida , pediatric endocrine scientist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm .
&quot; I spend a lot of time calming parents - normally this is no sign that now the puberty is rapidly entering , &quot; explained Kaplowitz .
obvious ads of development , such as growing breasts , sham- and ashes , as well as body smell , show up in girls earlier .
still , there was only a slight shift in the age of menarche ( occurrence of the first rule blood ) over the last 40 years .
in the United States , the average age is 12.5 years , slightly less than 12.75 in 1970 .
&quot; when the development of the breasts begins , it still takes at least two to three years to menarche , &quot; said Kaplowitz , also author of the book &quot; Early Puberty in Girls : the essential counselor to deal with this frequently occurring problem . &quot;
time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses .
it is controversial , which actually marks the beginning of puberty , but it is &quot; premature &quot; for breast enlargement to be accompanied by an increase of eight years ago .
in most cases , the process slows or stagnates - something a pediatrician can closely monitor .
in case of faster progress , tests could be displayed by an endikronologist , so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be excluded .
there are treatment methods for delaying an early menstruation and defenses of another episode : the early aging of the bones , which can ultimately lead to growth and thus small body growth in adults .
the recommendations for medication or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child , development speed , growth rate and emotional maturity .
psychosocial aspects are also important .
Kaplowitz is cautious about drugs , but he admits : &quot; the suppression of puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and the feelings of girls to be different from their peers . &quot;
the other big problem is understandable : parents simply don &apos;t want their very young daughters to have the period .
&quot; they worry about pregnancy risk or about how they handle the hygienic side , &quot; Kaplowitz said .
&quot; it was a shock , &quot; recalls a woman whose daughter got her days with 10 .
even though there were initial signs and we had talked about menstruation , she was emotionally unprepared .
she came terrified and excited from school home because she was the first in her circle of friends .
there are many widely publicized theories about the causes of early puberty .
but there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods , chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media would be cause .
young people come to puberty similar to girls earlier .
Kaplowitz believes the most compelling premise is the epidemic of obesity .
he supported the conduct of a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine , creating a link between body fat and entering puberty .
other studies support this conclusion , but there are many other factors that played a role .
in this country , African @-@ American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers .
there are different explanations for this .
global seems to have an early puberty influenced by all sorts of things , from economic conditions to climate to genes .
another mystery : although boys are growing facial and shamusement earlier , the trend towards full @-@ blown earlier puberty is not as pronounced as in girls .
other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the issue .
the emergence of acne and shamhaar is common even among babies and infants .
&quot; we need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty , &quot; said Dr. Lawrence Silverman , a pediatric endocrine scientist at Goryeb Children &apos;s Hospital in Morristown , New Jersey .
parents should not hesitate to be advised by their pediatrician how they should talk to their child .
&quot; that can mean you have to have a conversation sooner than expected , &quot; Mr. Kaplowitz advised .
if you stay calm , the child usually responds well .
girls who fled early need insurance , which the process is a normal part of life , even if it occurs earlier than thought .
jumbo manufacturers argue in the face of large orders over seat width
between leading aircraft manufacturers , there has been a clash over the breadth of seats in the tourist class on long @-@ haul flights , giving the tone for a bitter clash on the Dubai Airshow this month .
the dispute revolves around the seating range offered to passengers on long flights in the tourist class - not always those who seek the most airlines , but this designated space is the key to the efficiency of the latest Airbus SAS and Boeing Co .
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that requires a seating width of at least 46 cm ( 18 inches ) in the tourist class , but the US archrival Boeing says that should be the airlines &apos; choice .
the clash comes at a time when aircraft makers are weathering to sell even larger versions of their two @-@ engine long @-@ haul aircraft , and at the event expect record orders from November 17 to 21 .
how the rear part of the aircraft is designed - especially whether there are rows with nine or ten seats - is crucial to the economic results indicated to deliver the new &quot; mini @-@ jumbo &quot; design .
Boeing claims its modernized &quot; 777X &quot; fibre 406 people at seats in the tourist class , which are over 17 inches wide , allowing 10 per row .
Airbus declares that the competing version of the A350 is carrying 350 people in 18 inches wide seats in the tourist class , with nine per row .
aircraft giants often share Hiebe with technical details via advertising in the specialist press .
now Airbus is appealing directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow , where the 777X with over 100 orders is expected to make the race .
recently , the company unveiled an ad that could be the start of a new ad war and donors showed a picture in which three people clashed in a restaurant , and the title : &quot; would you accept that ? &quot;
&quot; Boeing is proposing long @-@ haul flights in seats that are closer than regional turbo @-@ props , &quot; says Airbus sales chief John Leahy .
given changed diet habits , people are becoming thicker , but aircraft seats have not changed radically .
between the early 1970s , when the Boeing 747 defined modern long @-@ haul travel , and the end of the century , the weight of the male average American increased by 10 percent between 40 and 49 years , according to data from the U.S. Department of Health .
the Tailleness of the male average American in the 21st century is 100.8 cm , according to U.S. health statistics .
Airbus says its rival is sticking to a seating concept from the 1950s , when the average body range of the freshly tinted &quot; Jet Set &quot; was narrower .
according to Airbus , investigations were carried out which showed that an additional inch ( 2.54 cm ) per seat would increase sleep quality by 53 percent .
Boeing denies Airbus figures to the seats and says it is not at the discretion of manufacturers to decide how airlines are shaping the balance between airline fares and establishment .
the company also explains , according to investigations , the experience on the plane depends on more than the seat width .
&quot; it really is running out to give airlines flexibility so they can do what they think they need to be successful , &quot; explains Boeing &apos;s air carrier expert Kent Craver .
they don &apos;t want us to dictate to them what makes them profitable .
they know their business better than anyone else .
passengers are about more elbow @-@ free , but for manufacturers it becomes increasingly an issue that can affect turnover .
behind the clash is a race for aircraft orders with an estimated volume of at least $ 700 billion after list prices in the coming decades , which could have a lasting impact on the US or Europe &apos;s export balance .
as Reuters first reported in July , the seat layout is the driving force behind the clash over the new jets .
both Airbus and Boeing claim 20 percent more efficiency per seat at their latest two @-@ engine long @-@ range designs than the market leader in this segment , the 365 @-@ seat Boeing 77 @-@ 300ER .
the statements Boeings made on the results are partly due to the fact that the 777X is compared with its 10 seats per row with the original design of nine seats in the 777 .
the increased costs per unit are still lower than those of currently used machines with ten seats per row .
&quot; Boeing is therefore squeezing more seats into its aircraft to make it more competitive to our products , &quot; says Kevin Keniston , head of passenger comfort at European Airbus .
on the other hand , analysts say , full cabins with ten seats per row at existing 777s indicated that many passengers opted for closer arrangement , which could involve cheaper air fares .
&quot; eighteen inches of seating would be great for passengers , but the reality is : from an economic point of view , the Airbus offer is controlled by the threat posed by the 777 , &quot; says Mary Kirby , an expert on cabin equipment , founder and editor of Runway Girl Network .
Airbus and Boeing do not offer seats , but a catalogue of suppliers from which airlines can choose .
the world @-@ wide jet vendors even contribute bandwidth to gauge the facility at the competition .
even if they price comfort , all manufacturers also offer jets with high @-@ density design for low @-@ cost airlines and regional flights .
Airbus offers a 10 @-@ seat A350 , but has not yet sold one .
until recently , Airbus has stressed the importance of more adaptability of cabins and offered broad seats on the aisles for some jets .
without the support of the only other manufacturer of large modern jets , experts say the call for a new industry standard is likely to fizzle , but could distract from the wave of 777X sales .
new anti @-@ nicotine vaccine could make the pleasure of smoking the guard
scientists have developed an anti @-@ nicotine vaccine that could spoil fun at smoking .
a single dose of the vaccine could protect mice a lifetime from nicotine addiction .
before tests on humans , further attempts are needed , which may take some years , but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good .
&quot; we are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit while trying out all the methods available on the market , but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches , &quot; Cornell concluded .
the new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been changed to include genetic information to produce nicotine antibodies .
the virus selectively infects the liver cells , which then produce a constant stream of antibodies .
the antibodies chase nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before reaching the brain , leaving a smoker not to learn nicotine high .
in trials , vaccinated mice administered by nicotine kept their normal levels of activity .
mice without vaccination , by contrast , had taken an &quot; out of time , &quot; the researchers said , a sign that the nicotine had reached her brain .
the experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine .
previous tobacco vaccines failed because they included antibodies .
the vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain the antibody that they were expensive and impractical .
but the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower because it turns liver cells into antibody convertibles .
as Professor Crystal said , a future vaccine for people , if quite certain , would be administered children before they were tempted to try a cigarette , thus preventing nicotine addiction .
more likely , though , is that smokers would use him to stop .
&quot; they then know : when they start smoking again , they feel no pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine , and that helps them to lay off the habit , &quot; he explains .
British scientists said the results were interesting but at the same time warned that further research was needed .
