rules on electronic equipment in aircraft remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian airline passengers must continue to shut down tablets and smartphones at launch and landing , despite efforts in the U.S. to loosen regulations on such devices .
the U.S. Federal Aviation Administration ( FAA ) allows U.S. airlines to change their specifications so passengers can read e @-@ books , watch or play videos on their devices during critical flight phases , provided they are in &quot; flight mode . &quot;
during most of the flight , passengers are already allowed to do so , but many people find it annoying that they are not allowed to read their e @-@ books when starting and landing .
Australian companies are monitoring the decision to implement them , but are not pursuing immediate plans to amend their rules .
CASA &apos;s air traffic control agency also said it will look at the announcement , but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices in critical flight phases in Australia still apply .
&quot; CASA currently has no specific regulations regarding the use of electronic devices on the aircraft , &quot; it was announced .
the issue is subject to provisions requiring airlines to maintain safety at any time and to comply with safety instructions given by cabin crew .
Virgin has already held talks with CASA about an extension of its Wi @-@ Fi entertainment system on flights and has said that it is open to change , but it must be initiated by the legislator .
&quot; we would welcome a review of the licensing of electronic devices by CASA because we are convinced this would improve customer experience after we now offer ( wireless entertainment ) during the flight , &quot; a spokesman said .
Qantas explained that you will stick to current regulations until further notice .
&quot; our current guidelines provide that electronic devices should not be used when starting and landing , and we currently have no plans to change that , &quot; the company said .
the FAA rules apply to U.S. airlines .
however , we are always interested in developments in regulations that allow passengers to benefit and will certainly look closely at the FAA decision and the reasons behind it .
the decision varies between US companies depending on the age of the fleet .
they must prove that their planes can tolerate the radio disruptions through mobile devices , and change manuals , training materials , hand baggage programs and customer support .
&quot; after an airline has confirmed the tolerance of its fleet , it can allow passengers to use portable , light electronic devices such as tablets , e @-@ book readers and smartphones at any rate , &quot; the FAA announced .
in rare cases in bad sight , the crew will instruct passengers to turn off the equipment while landing .
the group also recommended stowing heavier devices safely under the seat or in the subjects above the seat at launch and landing .
