Pfandbrief booms in Singapore as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
in a Pfandbrief in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore , Janani Amirthalinga swaps a golden wriggle , a ring and a pair of earrings to pay their daughters &apos; school fees .
&quot; my husband and I just bought a house , there &apos;s all my money in it , &quot; Amirthalinga says .
although she dived 3,000 Singapore dollars ( ca 1,730 euros ) each month as an administrative employee and her husband also works , the monthly family income is not enough , she explains .
indeed , demand in parts of Southeast Asia - where household debt is increasing - is so large that ValueMax , where it has made its exchange , became the third Pfandbrief listed on the singapuric stock exchange this week .
botched jewelry is not only a quick way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan .
typically , Pfandhouses in Singapore require an effective annual rate of 17 percent , just above the 15.4 percent required by United Overseas Bank , a local lender with a branch in the same shopping mall .
however , Pfandbrief offers the advantage that there is no need for a review of creditworthiness or income evidence , which is why loans can be made faster than banks .
this is why millions of people in the region are turning to Pfandhouses after families feel pressure from rising living costs as well as increased household and consumer debt .
after five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit , owing to loose fiscal policies in developed economies , families with lower and middle @-@ income mortgages are looking to offset the difference in stalling economies .
this week , the ratings agency called Standard &amp; Poor &apos;s growing fiscal debt , mainly due to rising mortgages , a risk factor for the credit rating of Asian banks .
Malaysia , Thailand and Singapore , according to the agency , have the highest household debt in Asia relative to gross domestic product .
Malaysia stands at 80 percent of GDP at the top of the list , an increase of 60 percent still in 2008 .
economists are also worried about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand , which this week has just come out of a technical recession .
on Thursday , the data showed continued export weakness and a drop in consumer demand .
&quot; ultimately , that means that given rising costs , people in the middle to lower segment ( the income scale ) will try to supplement their income wherever possible , &quot; says Song Seng Wun , economist at CIMB , a Malaysian bank .
historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have exacerbated the trend of eating personal items as people seize the opportunity to turn the family &apos;s jewelry into cash .
in Singapore , about 70 percent of botched items are gold in the city &apos;s 200 deposit houses .
people are saying : &quot; the price of gold looks good , let &apos;s forgo grandmother gold chain and get back next month . &quot;
the largest Thai Pfandbrief operator , easymoney , has experienced a 20 % increase in customer revenue in its branches in recent months .
growth in the Pfandbrief is so strong that ValueMax , operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore , wants to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia - where the company operates four homes - but also outside Asia , according to Yeah Lee Ching , managing director of ValueMax .
the company finances that with 60 percent of the $ 66 million Singapore dollar it took this week with the stock market in Singapore .
while some lenders have come to the crossfire because of high interest rates , Yeah explains that Pfandbrief would not only provide cheaper interest rates than other lending , but also not directly raised debt .
&quot; customers are offending items they already own , and the disappearance of personal valuables does not increase household debt , &quot; she explains .
the Pfandbrief business is socially increasingly accepted as short @-@ term , secured financing .
nor are all those who use Pfandbriefe in financial difficulties .
rich people from Singapore also come to the stores of ValueMax to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches , for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash .
customers come from every social layer .
&quot; these include wealthy people who borrow something for a business or an investment in the short term , or small businesses that need to bridge bottlenecks in cash flow , &quot; Yeah says .
sometimes they just need money very quickly .
