Syria has destroyed its ability to manufacture chemical weapons , according to a surveillance group
Syria destroyed key facilities to manufacture chemical weapons and grid gas munitions , the global surveillance group for chemical weapons said Thursday , while heavy clashes occurred in the north of the country near one of the sites where suspected toxic substances are stored .
also on Thursday , a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed soon three years ago since the start of the civil war .
the organization &apos;s announcement of the ban on chemical weapons ( OPCW ) came a day before the date on
1 November , which the organisation Damascus , based in The Hague , had set up to destroy or &quot; inoperable &quot; all facilities for the manufacture of chemical weapons , including all machinery for mixing chemicals into toxic gas and filling of ammunition .
the conclusion of this incident , which is basically the first stage of destruction , is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at destroying all Syria &apos;s chemical weapons by mid @-@ 2014 .
the destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons .
Damascus , however , has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and supplies .
there are about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country , including mustard gas and nerve gas sarin .
the announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday , experts say that there is a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities here , as the United Kingdom @-@ based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights reported .
the activist group , which tracks the number of deaths through a network of activists in Syria , said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died .
of these , 61,067 are civilians , including 6,365 children .
on the government side , 29,954 of them included the army of President Bashar Assad , 18,678 were pro @-@ government fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias .
also among the dead are 2,202 deserted army data and 5,375 opposition fighters , many of them foreigners .
on July 25 , the UN estimated the number of deaths in this conflict since March 2011 to 100,000 .
this number has not yet been updated .
the conflict has forced about two million people to flee the country .
Assad &apos;s forces have been fighting in Safira for weeks against the rebels , many of whom have ties to al @-@ Qaida groups .
the Observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday , but did not specify details .
the fighting underscores the danger the chemical weapons inspectors face , because their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time amid a deadly civil war .
according to the OPCW , which works closely with the United Nations , the team &quot; is now convinced that it has seen all of Syria &apos;s important production and mixing / filling facilities and witnessed its destruction . &quot;
therefore , no further inspection activities are currently planned . &quot;
earlier this week , inspectors said they had completed the first round of reviews and visited 21 of 23 of Damascus &apos;s sites .
because of security concerns , the visit of two facilities was not possible , the inspectors said .
on Thursday , OPWC said the two sites had been abandoned , according to Syrian statements , &quot; and the existing objects of the chemical weapons program there had been moved to other designated facilities that were inspected . &quot;
it was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities the OPCW inspectors could not visit .
Syria has put forward a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons , which must be approved by the OPWC &apos;s executive committee next month .
&quot; I pull the hat off the bravery and the courage you have all shown when completing the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organization , &quot; Ahmed Uzumcu , the director @-@ general of the monitoring organization , said in a commentary published by OPCW .
for the past three years , the mainly Sunni Muslim rebels have been fighting Assad &apos;s government and its security forces , which include many members of Alawites , a secession of Shiite Islam .
regarding further developments , the head of the observation group , Rami Abdurrahman , said there was a strong explosion at an air defense facility in Syria &apos;s coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday .
the cause of the explosion was not known , he explained .
