FAA : passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft ( but don &apos;t have mobile phone calls )
air travelers can now hear from departure to landing their electronic devices for reading , working , playing , music and using the reputation of movies , but not by phone , according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration ( FAA ) in the US .
but passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately .
how quickly they would be implemented , down from the respective airline , FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a news conference .
the airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new directives and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight staff as well as the regulations governing the storage of equipment in accordance with the new rules .
the FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft .
among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue .
&quot; depending on the state of the plan , we could approve extended use of electronic devices very soon , &quot; the FAA announced in a statement .
currently , passengers must shut off smartphones , tablets and other devices when the plane doors are closed .
they may not start them again until the plane reaches a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light .
when entering the landing flight , passengers must relinquish it and must not restart it before the aircraft has landed .
under the new guidelines , airlines whose planes are secured against electronic disturbances could allow their passengers to use the equipment even at launch , landing and on the rolling field , the FAA said .
most new transport aircraft and other planes adapted for use Wi @-@ Fi at greater heights should meet the criteria .
Laura Glading , president of the Professional Aircraft Association , welcomed the changes .
&quot; if the new arrangement is implemented safely - and we are working closely with the airline on this - both sides will benefit , &quot; commented Glading .
we are frankly sorry to have to feel like passers on this issue .
however , Internet connections for surfing , exchanging e @-@ mails , text messages or downloading data under three kilometres remained prohibited , the authority explained .
passengers are urged to place smartphones , tablets and other devices in flight mode .
so still no &quot; Words With Friends , &quot; the Scrabble resembles an online game played by actor Alec Baldwin in 2011 on his smartphone , when he had to leave high @-@ profile a jet by American Airlines because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked at the airstrip .
and heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be dusted , as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin .
mobile phone calls during the flight also remain banned .
the regulatory competence for phone calls is with the Federal Communications Commission ( FCC ) , not with the FAA .
FAA suspends possibly banning certain electronic devices at launch and landing
last month Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board , security expert on national transport issues on CBS News , said cell phones would still be considered a risk .
&quot; mobile phones are really a problem , not just because they could potentially cause disruption to navigation devices , but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmissions , &quot; Rosenker added .
an industry advisory committee created by the FAA to investigate this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices .
in recent years , pressure on the FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use .
critics such as Democratic Sen. Claire McCaskill from Missouri take the view that there are no valid security reasons for the ban .
the restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of equipment has become ubiquitous .
some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers may forget or ignore the switch @-@ off of the device .
the FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travelers after reports of disruptions of navigation and communication equipment by passenger @-@ led UKW radios that were the latest technology trend at the time .
new aircraft are far more dependent on electric systems than previous generations of aircraft , but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they do not constitute electronic interference .
airlines have been providing Wi @-@ Fi to passengers for several years when the flight level has reached .
the aircraft adapted to Wi @-@ Fi systems are also more vulnerable to interferences .
the vast majority of passenger aircraft should be eligible for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines , Huerta said .
today &apos;s electronic devices generally give much less radio coverage than previous generations .
e @-@ readers , for example , only give up minimal radiation when you &apos;re umbling .
but when downloading or sending data , the transmission values are stronger .
advocates of easing restrictions on the use of equipment by passengers include Amazon.com.
in 2011 , company employees invited a passenger plane full of Kindle e @-@ readers and made a test flight to identify problems but could not find any .
members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment .
Douglas Kidd of the passenger association National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption from the devices is real , even if the risk is minimal .
other county officials said there were only isolated reports of pilots preaching for a disruption of aircraft systems by the devices , and most of them are very old .
the committee , however , recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange the removal of the equipment by passengers when landing in poor visibility .
a group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and called them a reasonable adjustment for travelers who would now be extensively equipped with technology .
&quot; we are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety , &quot; said Roger Dow , CEO of the U.S. Travel Association .
