is Europe &apos;s elite ready to do business with Britain ?
business for Britain was launched in April with the intention of bringing the economy to a table and defining what those in Britain want to change in our relations with the EU .
to this end , we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey among British business leaders and asked them what they think about Britain , the economy and the EU .
YouGov surveyed over 1,000 executives from the economy , accounting for about the UK &apos;s corporate sizes , sectors and regions .
the results of the poll will surprise many .
we found that the vast majority of companies now export outside Europe and focus on countries that modernize and grow while EU countries are stagnating .
they hope that new trade links with countries such as China , India and Brazil will be favored by government , rather than halting the long and exhausting process of reforming the obscure EU institutions .
when asked about their view on certain legally regulated issues - from antitrust to product legislation - the majority of business leaders believe that control of these key competences should be recovered to Westminster .
there was general dissatisfaction about the internal market , because , according to companies , the costs of the Brussels rules would now outweigh the benefits of being part of Europe &apos;s trading zone - even 40 % of large companies agreed to what is traditionally the most pro @-@ European .
finally , and presumably most , our survey of business leaders showed that a clear majority of Britain wants a course towards changing the agreement and that a relationship with the EU based on trade is not on politics .
this finding , found among companies of all sizes and leading corporations , shows that the economy is pushing for a &quot; meaningful change &quot; that will bring the stalemate of action back to Britain .
it &apos;s all about much - a change in the agreement and better conditions for Britain would lead to a 16 percent change of opinion in favour of staying in the EU in a referendum .
the Prime Minister should have no doubt : this survey shows that the UK economy is behind its plan for renegotiating UK conditions for EU membership .
it also shows that companies expect a renegotiation of power back to Britain .
a better deal for the UK economy is possible and increasingly necessary now that the eurozone is moving towards closer economic and fiscal union .
the priority must be jobs and growth in the UK , as the result of our survey shows , which means greater focus on trade and a fundamental change in the Brussels approach to regulation .
