scientists were able to shed more light on the context in which the tail of a dog stands with its mood .
previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail waved more to the right ( from the point of view of the dog ) , while it was left with nervous dogs .
but now scientists say other dogs perceive these subtle differences and can respond to them .
Professor Georgio Vallortigara , a neuroscientist at the University of Trient , said : &quot; in humans it is well known that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that generate positive or negative emotions . &quot;
here we tried to look at this with other species .
he also noted that dogs , like humans , have the right brains for the movement of the left , and vice versa , and that the two hemispheres played different roles in feelings .
to learn more about how dogs respond to the lateral tail of their counterparts , the researchers monitored the animals while these films of other dogs were beheaded .
they measured the heart rate of the foursomes and analyzed the behavior .
probably we &apos;ll soon understand why the tail moves in one direction , sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said : &quot; we showed the dogs films with dogs - either a natural version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects , and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right . &quot;
when the animals saw how an otherwise printable dog moved the tail to the right ( seen from the perspective of the waving dog ) , they remained completely relaxed .
but was the tail tendency mainly to the left ( again from the perspective of the dog who waved ) , so their heart rate rose and they looked unsettled .
according to Professor Vallortigara , the dogs do not deliberately communicate with each other through these movements .
on the contrary , he is convinced that the dogs had learned from experience on which movements they should worry and when not .
he said : &quot; if you have different encounters with other dogs and the Wedding is associated with the tail in one direction more with friendly behavior and the right side produces more of a less friendly behavior , then you respond on the basis of these experiences . &quot;
researchers say the findings could help dog owners , vets and trainers understand their animal &apos;s emotions better .
John Bradshaw , an expert on dog behaviour and guest pencil at the Faculty of Animal Care at the University of Bristol , said this was not the first study to examine whether left and right was important for dogs .
last year , a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they watch an aggressive dog , and to the right when it &apos;s a satisfied dog .
in another research work at the University of Victoria in Canada , the following said : &quot; dogs are more likely to go on a robotic dog when his , tail &quot; left waved and not right , rather than become unsettled - exactly different than in the Italian study . &quot;
according to his statement , the differences could therefore stir that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs .
a study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help , he explained .
&quot; while there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brains are used for different purposes , many of the details still need to be determined - and dogs are no exception , &quot; Bradshaw added .
since their behaviour is easy to record , it will probably not take long for us to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction , sometimes in the other .
