despair of an Obama voter
I chose President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible
he says Obama has made commendable efforts , which have been thwarted by the House Republican &apos;s blockade agenda
the blockade policy does not apologize to Obamacare &apos;s website problems , the drone strikes
Obama &apos;s memoir about the 2008 campaign is a sad reminder of what might have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a student in the second year at Harvard Medical School .
I &apos;m currently reading a terribly sad book .
it &apos;s a book I believed it would heal me during the gloomy second year of my medical degree and give me hope again .
it is called &quot; The Audacity to Win &quot; ( courage to win ) and describes Barack Obama &apos;s memoir on the 2008 presidential election .
when I &apos;m finished with my patient &apos;s records and going to bed in the evening , the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and smoked my breath .
the election became a landslide victory and news spokesman held to highlight the historical significance of that hour .
my classmates wept before joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find .
a young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change .
when Obama moved to office in 2008 , he had approval ratings of 82 % .
and then I close the book .
turning back on the present is a bad awakening as if you are being taken out of a dream .
it &apos;s hard to remember these optimistic times - they seem to be a vague reminder , a sad reminder of missed opportunities .
in the years since I first cast my vote , something has actually changed .
but it &apos;s just nothing I could have imagined .
I recognise the great and versatile things Obama has achieved , from passing the Affordable Care Act on health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq , the end of forced secrecy in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden .
I , too , believe that the partisan block debate has overturned too many aspirations with which our nation should move forward : immigration reform , a public option for health insurance and closing Guantanamo Bay , to name just a few .
but having defended the Obama administration many times against colleagues and acquaintances , I came to the end with my explanations .
I have reached a point of political despair .
Republican blockade politics cannot explain why to allow foreign leaders to intercept or kill innocent children by drones overseas .
it cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are punished , which disclose government wrongdoing .
it cannot explain why Anwar al @-@ Awlaki , a US citizen , was murdered without trial , nor why public funding and exit limits will be circumvented during the presidential elections .
it does not justify the results of a report that says the White House &apos;s efforts to ruin the media are the &quot; most aggressive ... since the Nixon government . &quot;
and most recently , it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act .
I don &apos;t know if it &apos;s what I should have expected .
whether I should have understood with 18 that government work could contradict its previous political campaigns .
obviously , the Members &apos; Office is not a predictable course , as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape public debate .
but when I look at the above examples , they seem largely elected by the government itself .
and that bothers me most .
I chose Obama again in 2012 , not because I was thrilled about his candidacy .
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unexplained alternative , saying he didn &apos;t seem to set his direction and positions .
I had the impression that a second term for Obama , free of pressure from future elections , would meet the hope of which we had heard for so long .
but with the sinking of approval ratings for Obama to below 45 % this week , returning to 2008 through this book has become all the tougher .
it awakens in me the yearning for the many promises that have broken up in air .
this week I read a section in the book describing how Obama had to plug a serious loss against Clinton in the primaries in Pennsylvania .
in a meeting with election supporters after the decision , he told his staff they had to get back on course and follow the purpose of their cause .
&quot; I want us to rediscover our spell , &quot; he said .
we have to remember who we are .
it &apos;s five years later , Mr. President , and I couldn &apos;t agree more to you .
the views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris .
