RBS suspends two foreign exchange traders
the Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange division , according to two people familiar with the situation ; this is another indication that the global government investigation into the alleged manipulation of the currency market is rapidly taking off .
some of the world &apos;s largest banks , including UBS , Barclays , Deutsche Bank and RBS , confirmed they were working with authorities on the investigation into the world &apos;s largest financial market , on which 5.3 trillions of dollars a day change the owner .
the two dealers would be the first RBS staff to be suspended in the expanding investigation , which follows the scandal surrounding Libor interbank business .
the bank , which did not comment on the suspensions , confirmed this month that it had received information requests from authorities .
&quot; our investigation into this issue continues and we are cooperating fully with the FCA and other regulators , &quot; the bank said two weeks ago .
last month , the situation surrounding people indicated that RBS had forwarded the records of e @-@ mails and instant messages sent by and to a former retailer to the UK regulator , the Financial Conduct Authority .
this trader , Richard Usher , had left RBS in 2010 and is now said to have been judged by his current position as European head of Forex spot trading at JPMorgan .
Rohan Ramchandani , head of European spot trading at Citi , was judged this week and Matt Gardiner , formerly senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS , was suspended at Standard Chartered this week .
none of these traders have been accused of any wrongdoing .
asked about Usher &apos;s instant message group , bankers at Barclays and Citigroup said the situation was approaching people .
UBS announced this week that it was taking steps against some of its employees after Swiss regulator FINMA said it was looking into alleged manipulation of the foreign exchange market at a number of Swiss banks .
at least six authorities worldwide - the European Commission , FINMA , the Swiss competition authority WeKo , the FCA , the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are currently dealing with allegations that bankers should have agreed to deal with transactions in the currency market .
HSBC , Citigroup , JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have also launched internal investigations or received information requests from authorities , said people familiar with the situation .
banks muddled Instant Messages and e @-@ mails from several years in search of cases of wrongdoing .
news about these investigations has put traders in turmoil in an area that has in recent years been one of the most profitable of the trading units of investment banks , but has been under pressure this year because low volatility in currencies is limiting opportunities for speculators .
some bankers have tried to downplay the affair , saying that it is almost impossible to manipulate the extensive and highly liquid foreign exchange market , but leading traders believe that this is not necessarily true .
a leading retailer noted that , despite the enormous daily volume of foreign exchange trading , the fragmentation of liquidity between the various trading platforms and the increasing use of domestic platforms by banks leads to &quot; already having very low ticket prices . &quot;
the news came out the same day when Credit Suisse announced it had terminated a retailer of its London Exchange Traded Funds office this week after causing a loss of just under $ 6 million at the end of last year .
the bank promptly informed the competent authorities and worked with them .
&quot; we are sure the retailer acted alone and that the matter is contained , &quot; Credit Suisse explained .
