Google , Samsung , Huawei sued for Nortel patents
the group , which owns thousands of former Nortel patents , on Thursday filed an avalanche of lawsuits for patent infringement against mobile phone manufacturers , including Google , the company that was overbid by Nortel in the bankruptcy auction .
Rockstar , the consortium that had bought the Nortel patents for $ 4.5 billion , sued Samsung Electronics Co Ltd , HTC Corp , Huawei and four other companies for patent violations before the U.S. District Court in Texas .
Rockstar is jointly owned by Apple , Microsoft , BlackBerry , Ericsson and Sony .
Google is accused in seven cases of patent infringement .
the patents apply to technology that matches search terms on the Internet with relevant advertising , according to the lawsuit , which affects the core of Google &apos;s search engine business .
representatives from Samsung , Huawei , HTC and Rockstar were not immediately reachable .
Samsung , Huawei and HTC are making mobile phones that work with Google &apos;s Android operating system , which is in sharp competition with Apple &apos;s and Microsoft &apos;s mobile products .
in 2011 , Google announced an initial bid for $ 900 million for Nortel patents .
Google increased its offer several times and last offered $ 4.4 billion .
after being handed over to Rockstar &apos;s Nortel patents , Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $ 12.5 billion , a deal that was also partly motivated by Motorola &apos;s library to patents .
&quot; although Google has failed with its attempt to acquire the plea at auction , Google has violated the patents and continues to do so , &quot; the plea said .
Rockstar is demanding high compensation from Google as it claims Google &apos;s patent infringement is deliberate , according to the allegation .
Egypt sworn in first freely elected president
Mohammed Morsi sets the oath of office , but his day of triumph is not likely to mark the end of political disputes in Egypt .
Islamist Mohammed Morsi promised a &quot; new Egypt &quot; when he was sworn in as the country &apos;s first freely elected president and thus joined the succession of Husni Mubarak , who had been expelled from office 16 months earlier .
with his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court , Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamist president of the Arab world and Egypt &apos;s fifth head of state since the fall of the monarchy about 60 years ago .
he placed the oath in front of the 18 black robes of the court , which has its seat on the Nile and has been recreated by an ancient Egyptian temple .
&quot; we are striving for a better future , a new Egypt and a second republic , &quot; Morsi said at the formal ceremony , which was broadcast live on state television .
&quot; today , the Egyptian people laid the foundations for a new life - absolute freedom , genuine democracy and stability , &quot; said 60 @-@ year @-@ old Morsi , an engineer trained in the US and a member of the Muslim Brotherhood , a fundamentalist group that had been targeted mostly as a banned organization by the government since its inception 84 years ago .
hundreds of soldiers and police guarded the building when Morsi arrived in a small car convoy shortly after 11 a.m. local time .
only a few hundred supporters had gathered in the court to cheer up the new president , and unlike the presidential Prunk from the Mubarak era , traffic was stopped short of time so that the car convoy could cross the usually bustling road linking the city centre with the southern suburbs .
as the Brotherhood &apos;s uncharismatic &quot; spare wheel , &quot; his personal prestige has increased since his victory and a Friday speech in which he presented himself not only as a candidate for Islamists , but all those who wanted to target the aspirations of the 2011 uprising against authoritarian Mubarak .
&quot; Egypt is now a civilian , national , constitutional , and modern state , &quot; declared Morsi , dressed in a blue suit with red tie , to the judges in the wood @-@ fired chamber in which he dismissed the oath of office .
later , Morsi drove to the University of Cairo , where he was supposed to deliver his inaugural address .
he was officially greeted by an army commander who played the national anthem he listened to in hailing .
