travelling through mud , rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr Georges Bwave brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwave and his team spend nearly every weekend treating hundreds of patients
there are not many doctors in the West African country , just one for 5,000 people
vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwave is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013 .
you can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to elect him to the CNN Hero of the Year .
the winner receives $ 250,000 to continue his extraordinary work .
for 21 years , Georges Bwave looked at how his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him .
Jamef Bwave was injured in a car crash near Yaoundé , the capital Cameroon , in 1981 .
at first , he had only one broken arm , but then formed an inflammation that extended to his brain and caused a hematom there that should affect him for the rest of his life .
&quot; there were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon , &quot; Georges Bwave said .
we would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had had the money .
instead , Bwave spent years accompanying his father in crowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer .
&quot; it &apos;s not easy , &quot; Bwave commented .
you can leave the house at 5 a.m. and run to the hospital to be the first , and is not the first .
there are very many patients .
some people even die because they have to wait .
the situation has barely changed since Bwelles &apos;s father died in 2002 .
in Cameroon , there is only one doctor for every 5,000 people , according to the World Health Organization .
on the other hand , the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people .
but even if there was a doctor for them , most cameramen could not afford to visit .
two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three @-@ quarters of health spending in the country is private .
&quot; the only problem they have is poverty , &quot; Bwave says .
and poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life .
to see his father and so many of his compatriots suffer in Bwelle , the decision to do something about it .
Dr Georges Bwave and his volunteer carried out 700 free operations last year .
he became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Central Hospital in Yaoundé .
he also founded a nonprofit organization called ASCOVIME , which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there .
since 2008 , he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people .
almost every Friday , he and up to 30 people forced themselves into minibuses and drive with the snowy medical equipment on the roof over unfortified terrain to the villages that need help .
not always running smoothly .
for more than once , they had to push vehicles through rivers and mud .
but when they arrive , they will receive like heroes : a festive meal , singing and dance and the best accommodation the place has to offer .
in these villages , free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and blow - with its broad smile and boundless energy - is happy to attend the happy celebration .
the next morning the team then begins investigating hundreds of patients .
&quot; per ride we treat 500 people , &quot; Bwelle said .
they come from a distance of 60 kilometres around the village - and that is on foot .
each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas .
many people are treated for malaria , tuberculosis , malnutrition , diabetes , parasites and sexually transmitted diseases .
others get crutches , donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for the school but many poor families simply can &apos;t afford .
in the evening , the team performs simple operations with local anesthetic .
the operations usually take place in a school , town hall or apartment ; after the operation , patients stand up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next .
lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is fed by the group &apos;s generator and so Bwave and his volunteers work until early morning hours on Sunday .
it &apos;s an exhausting pencil , but village musicians usually help keep the team motivated .
&quot; they trot all night so we can stay awake and continue our work , &quot; says Bwave .
on Sunday the team then returns to the city , tired but proud of the work done .
the group - a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free operations last year and knows that , with its work , it makes a huge difference for the people it helps .
a man explained that the free operation of a boardwalk he received now allowed him to work again .
&quot; this changes the future of my family , &quot; the man said .
in addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon at the hospital , Bwave also works at private clinics in Yaoundé at night .
with this second job , he finances 60 % of his nonprofit business , according to Bwelve ; the rest come from private donations .
&quot; I really don &apos;t know when he sleeps , &quot; says Katie O &apos;Malley , who studied medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and volunteered in Bwelles Group .
he is always in hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns .
for medical and health care students such as O &apos;Malley , who come from the US and Europe and support Bwave , this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home .
&quot; we can be at operations where we help cover blood or keep the instruments for Dr. Bwelle , &quot; O &apos;Malley explains .
that would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year .
students usually pay their journey to Cameroon themselves and bring frequently donated sanity material .
however , once they are in Yaoundé , Bwave takes over accommodation , transport and guidance .
&quot; he &apos;s definitely a hero , &quot; O &apos;Malley says .
he dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries .
for Bwave , almost permanent work is not a burden .
giving others a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he gave to his father gives him great pleasure .
&quot; I &apos;m so happy when I do this work , &quot; Bwave thinks .
and I think of my father .
I hope he sees what I do .
I do it to get people to laugh again and to alleviate the pain .
visit ASCOVIME &apos;s website and learn how to help .
excellently mastered the fight
the role of Santiago , the old man in Hemingway &apos;s Novelle &quot; The Old Man and the Sea , &quot; is Horst Janson cut to the body .
