tourism : descent to the Romans
at about 120 metres in length , a sewage channel from Roman times is preserved below Cologne .
those who visit Cologne do not pass the cathedral .
about 157 metres , the two towers raged into the sky , making it the second @-@ highest church building in Europe .
but few visitors who marvel at the two filigree church towers suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral .
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne &apos;s underworld .
meeting point for his guided tours is the service centre of Cologne @-@ Tourism , right on the cathedral .
the tour begins quite unspectacular : &quot; we start in the underground car park , &quot; Schulze says .
in the seventies , the city &apos;s fathers wanted an autojust city , and therefore the remains of the old city wall remained just what was not too big .
most of the users of the car park are now also passing the Roman remains and only stop their car .
but if you look more closely , the D2 parking deck will detect an archaeological site separated by the metal grid .
you can see about five feet tall ruins of hand @-@ made stones .
&quot; it is remnants of the Roman city wall built in the second half of the first century after Christ , &quot; Schulze told me .
before going back to daylight , Schulze lets attendees at the upper parking level still take a look in a sinister , 15 feet deep shaft .
this is the fountain of the old cathedral , which is unfortunately hardly perceived .
next station of the roundabout is the Pretorium , and here participants get back down to depth .
we see here the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps , the precursor of the CCAA .
what CCAA means is a visitor wants to know .
&quot; the abbreviation stands for &quot; Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium , &quot; which in good German means &quot; city Roman law and city of Agrippinenser , founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor . &quot;
and the Pretorium is the former statue palace , the centre of the Roman empire on the Rhine .
from the front of the exhibition there is a tunnel access to the Roman sewage channel , which is preserved here at about 120 metres .
&quot; you can quietly depart a piece along the so @-@ called Cloaca Maxima if you want , &quot; Schulze told guests .
a surprise still has Schulze .
after picking up the key at the box office , he leads the group to a 16 @-@ metre deep , walk @-@ in shaft .
&quot; we are now in the Mikwe , a ritual Jewish bath , &quot; he explains .
the Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing .
to date , in the lower end of the micro , whose origins date back to the eighth century , different water levels are readable by changing pegel of the Rhine .
the Mikwe will be part of an archaeological zone in Town Hall Square , for which construction work is due to begin shortly .
until completion , however , some years will pass .
