John Kerry declares in an unprecedented admission that the U.S. espionage has gone &quot; inappropriate too far &quot;
John Kerry hinted with an unexpected admission a softening of the US &apos;s defensive stance on its surveillance programs , saying the espionage had gone &quot; unduly too far &quot; in certain cases .
the foreign minister also admitted that he , along with Barack Obama , was guilty of being switched to &quot; autopilot &quot; when the explosive revelations of whistleblower Edward Snowden about the NSA &apos;s spy activities became public .
through leaked information , the U.S. government has come into a diplomatic storm of outrage from its allies .
speaking by video link at the Open Government conference in London , Kerry said : &quot; without question , the president and I , as well as others in the government , have learned of some things that have almost expired by autopilot , simply because the ability to do so was what still happened to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and , of course , to September 11 . &quot;
he then acknowledged as the first senior member of the US government that the US espionage had crossed a border , but also stressed that no rights had been abused .
he said : &quot; in some cases this has gone too far . &quot;
the President is determined to provide clarity and therefore carries out a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that abuse is taking place here .
I assure you that the rights of innocent people will not be affected in this process .
Kerry insisted , however , that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved by its surveillance operations .
he added : &quot; we are dealing with a new world where people are willing to splash themselves into the air . &quot;
there is radical extremism in the world that has failed to kill people , spill into the air and attack governments .
so what if you were able to intercept and stop it before it happens ?
we actually prevented plane crashes , attacks on buildings and the killing of people because we learned about such plans in advance .
meanwhile , U.S. lawmakers will travel to Europe to allay concerns about the alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to work with the U.S. on anti @-@ terrorism efforts , the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said Thursday .
Senator Chris Murphy from Connecticut said he spoke this week with representatives of the European Parliament and other people and was concerned about their threats to stop participating in anti @-@ terrorism organizations because of frustration over surveillance by the National Security Agency .
&quot; it is very important for the US national security interests that Europeans remain on board in terms of our joint efforts against terrorism , &quot; Murphy , who is serving as a Democrat for the first time in the Senate and acting as chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs , said in an interview in Washington .
I also go to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism , regardless of their anger over the NSA programmes .
media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have impacted relations with some U.S. allies , although the head of the intelligence service this week said the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of metadata collected by Nato allies and exchanged with the United States .
other revelations cited from Snowden &apos;s wider documents that the NSA monitored Chancellor Angela Merkel &apos;s mobile phone and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide .
the head of national intelligence , James clapper , defended the espionage among allies as necessary and said this was common on both sides .
in all the tumult , Murphy said his authority was preparing the Congress &apos; trip to take place this year and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers .
the names of the other participating Members will be published in the coming days .
he said the exact itinerary is still being worked out .
while Murphy stressed that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations , he also talked about there being some &quot; serious words . &quot;
he said that European governments should be honest with their people about the kind of espionage programmes they themselves have used for years .
&quot; while we can change our surveillance programmes and protect Europeans &apos; rights better , they also have to cope with the fact that we are not the only ones spiking , &quot; Murphy concluded .
meanwhile , John Kerry faces a trip to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to address the resentment of the US strategy in Syria , Egypt and Iran , as well as US surveillance activities .
