Australian sets appeal against prison sentence in Thailand
a 21 @-@ year @-@ old woman from Sydney who was sentenced to 15 days in prison in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been raped by a taxi driver has appealed against the ruling and has been released on bail .
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by a provincial court in Phuket on June 15 of making a false statement after she told Thai police a local taxi driver raped her in the morning hours on Sunday , June 10 , while two other men held her .
later , however , the footage of a video camera showed she had safely reached her hotel after being separated from her Australian boyfriend .
police in Phuket interrogated Bamford for two days until they confessed to having thought out the story .
until the trial , she was in police custody on the ground .
Bamford was sentenced to a 15 @-@ day prison sentence in a detention centre with low security levels on the outskirts of Phuket , rather than in a prison for adult women .
she is the daughter of Peter Tunks , a former player in the Australian Rubgy League who contacted the State Department in Canberra with asking for help for his daughter .
Tunks told the Sunday Telegraph in Sydney that the whole family was &quot; extremely concerned &quot; about his daughter &apos;s welfare and wanted her back in Australia .
&quot; we &apos;re obviously worried about it , but we hope it &apos;s back home as soon as possible , &quot; Tunks said .
Bamford has appealed against the ruling and is on a bail of 50,000 Baht at large .
in Australian reports , it was read that in the meantime it is holiday in the resort of Krabi in southern Thailand .
the court heard that Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and had been warned that the appeal could also lead to a higher sentence of up to two years in a prison for adults .
however , it is also possible that after the recent assassination of the travel clerk Michelle Smith in Phuket , Thailand may be trying to improve its troubled tourist image , and that is why it is becoming an acquittal .
